Title of Article/Chapter/Essay: Capital City Lodge Of Elks Enters New Second St. Home
Transcription of Printed Material: Capital City Lodge of Elks Enters New Second St. Home.  Formally Dedicated Sunday September 28, 1930.  The Capital City Lodge Elks, received congratulations from various clubs and fraternal organizations here during the open-celebration of their home at 526 N. Second street. The home is situated in the heart of the Negro business section of Richmond, being situated between Clay and Leigh streets, across the street from the Commercial Bank and Trust Co., between the Hippodrome and Globe theatre's. A brief description of the home is as follows: On entering the front door, not he left is a ladies rest room and parlor, which is fitted out with modern comfortable chairs, lounge, library table and piano.  The chairs and lounge being upholstered in tapestry and Jacquard velour, on the right is the gents maker and Billiard room equipped with Cigar stand, three cushion billiard tables and all the accoutrements that go in to make a modern and up to date billiard room.  To the rear of the billiard room is found the well stocked Cafeteria and Grill, uncharge of the efficient Steward, Mr. Junius Jones: to the left of the Grill across the hall is the Card room, where members may indulge in social games for their amusement.  Close inspection of this room convinced the writer that most Capital City members are very fond of Dominoes.  On the second floor to our left at the landing we find Mr. Frye's Barber-shop, next to which is found the Secretary's Office, where Mr. Green seems to be the dominant figure; going to the front we find a porch which gives a most magnificent view of the Negro business section of Richmond, the Auditorium and Dance hall occupied the entire right side of the second floor, with a raised dais in the extreme front end for the accommodation of the orchestra, the check-room being in the extreme rear. Benjamin Temple ladies occupy the front portion across the hall from the auditorium.  No use describing this part of the building as you all know how the ladies fix up their rooms.  On the third floor is found the Band room, two committee rooms, the Library and the Directors room.  The furniture and fixtures in the directors room "just wont dont," across the hall from the directors room is found the Library where we get another grand view of Richmond's Negro Broadway, and where we are afraid many of the members who have left their best days behind them will develop "cricks in the neck" from "looking em over."  There is to be found, unusual conveniences for women and men alike on each floor of the building.  On the whole the Elks of Capital City lodge deserve the credit and commendation which has so lavishly been bestowed on them by the populace, for the home is a finely appointed and as elaborately furnished, as any that we have seen in these parts.  More power to the Capital City lodge Elks in general and to "Tom Ellis," and his Board of Directors in particular.
(Photographs of the Senior Class of 1929)

Biography from Find-a-Grave linked above: Coleridge Davis was the pianist for the big band, Coleridge Davis & his Hardy Brothers Washingtonians. He played in many clubs from the eastern shore to Chicago during the 1940s including the Atlantic Follies of 1946 and the Bali Club in Baltimore. According to the World of Count Basie, Davis's group was their main competition in Atlantic City. Davis produced and costarred in the 1928 edition of Sugar Cane, a production that toured the Majestic Theatrical Circuit (white). Johnny Pate, the noted arranger and bassist, played with his band during a period in the 1940s. As a band that played with many revues of the time, many notable black entertainers such as Moms Mabley were on the program of the day. Louis Armstrong played with the band in 1943. The band was the house band at the Rhumboogie, a famous club and record label, in Atlantic City.

Notes and Clarifications:
Richmond Times-Dispatch Aug. 24th, 1915
Albert Clay, Colored, Dies From Knife Thrust at Hands of Another Negro.
Albert Clay, colored, was so seriously stabbed by Magnus Jenkins, another negro, at 2100 North Twenty-first Street last night that he died an hour later at Virginia Hospital. The scene of the stabbing was just outside the city limits. 
Clay was stabbed in the left arm, an artery being severed. Ambulance Surgeon Anderson gave first aid at the scene and took the injured man to the hospital. He had lost so much blood that he died ten minutes after being placed on the operating table. The stabbing occurred about 7 o'clock.
Chief of Police Seay, of Henrico County, with Policemen Jones and Hanky, of the local force, succeeded in locating Jenkins early this morning in a house on Thirty-first Street, between P and Q Streets. They arrested Jenkins there and later locked him in the County Jail, where he is being held pending arraignment before a magistrate to-day. Jenkins refused last night to discuss the cutting.

Richmond Times-Dispatch August 27, 1915
Magnus Jenkins Must Answer for Stabbing to Death Albert Clay.
Magnus Jenkins, the negro who last Monday night fatally cut Albert Clay, another negro, at Woodville, just outside of the city limits, was given a preliminary hearing yesterday morning before Magistrate H. S. Sunday, and sent on to the grand jury of the Henrico Circuit Court at the October term. Jenkins was remanded to jail without bail. 
According to the evidence adduced at the hearing, Jenkins was sitting on a porch talking to a negro girl when Clay came up and joined the party. Soon afterwards the two men began to quarrel over a women, and Jenkins pulled out his knife and stabbed his victim in the side, severing a blood vessel under the left arm. Clay was rushed to the Virginia Hospital, but died within a few minutes after reaching there. The arrest was made by Chief of Police T. Wilson Seay.
In 1915, Magnus was convicted for murder. Newspaper entries are uploaded.

Title of Newspaper/Book/Magazine: History of the American Negro and his institutions, Virginia Edition
Transcription of Printed Material: The year following his graduation, he began the practice in Richmond, where he has since resided. He took an active part in college athletics while in school and played both baseball and football. On Sept. 23, 1913, Dr. Calloway was happily married to Miss Ernestine Christian of Richmond. She was educated in the home schools and was before her marriage an accomplished teacher. They have two children, Samuel D., Jr., and William Calloway. In politics, Dr. Calloway is a Republican. He is a member of the Baptist Church and belongs to the Elks. He holds membership in the Old Dominion Dental Association, the Richmond Medical Society and the Peter B. Ramsey Dental Society. He is a member of the N. A. A. C. P.

Title of Newspaper/Book/Magazine: History of the American Negro and his institutions, Virginia Edition
Transcription of Printed Material: SAMUEL D. CALLOWAY Dr. Samuel Dismond Calloway, one of the energetic and successful young dentists of Richmond, has firmly established himself in a good practice and enters heartily into the professional, business and social life of the city. Not a few young men think it necessary, after going through college, to go away from home in order to succeed. a few, however, take up the work of life and succeed in their native towns, among those who know their characters and understand their abilities best. Dr. Calloway is among this number. He was born at Richmond, Nov. 10, 1885. His parents were John and Ella (Tinsley) Calloway. John Calloway was a son of Mary Calloway, while Ella Tinsley was a daughter of Carolina Tinsley. As a boy, young Calloway attended the local public schools, from which he passed to Virginia Union University, where he took the preparatory course. Thus equipped, he matriculated at Howard University, Washington, D. C., for his dental course, and won his D. D. S. degree in 1912. By hard work and close economy, he was able to maintain himself in school and complete his course without a break.

Transcription of Printed Material: The Death of Mr. Willie Hobson. In the memory of my husband, Willie Hobson, who departed this life Friday, January 19, 1917. He leaves a wife, one sister, two brothers, and a host of friends and relatives to mourn their loss. —His Wife, Sarah Hobson

Notes and Clarifications: Last name appears to be Hobson, not Hopkins, despite spelling on death certificate and headstone. Marker_Transcription: In Memory of | My Wife | Wife of | William Dandridge | Age 64 Years | Asleep in Jesus

Comments: The lower front left corner above the base has a small chip out of it, which appears to have had some attempt at reattachment.
Other Description: Pedestal with vaulted top, or vaulted obelisk. The rising part of the obelisk is plain polished granite, but the lowest section of the base has a rusticated finish on the sides and a beveled top. The upper section of the base has polished sides and a beveled top. Also, the top of the obelisk appears to be peaked, although it has been weathered until it is somewhat rounded.
Decoration: There are two centered underlines between script lines; they follow the seventh and eighth (last) lines. Also, the stone is cut back at the top of the monument to leave a raised triangular peak. This repeats on the sides of the statue and gives the impression of a stylized crown.
Full transcription as it appears on the: IN MEMORY OF | MY WIFE | MATILDA | WIFE OF | WILLIAM DANDRIDGE | DIED NOV. 14 1898 | AGE 64 YEARS | ASLEEP IN JESUS
Other Associated artifacts, plantings, o: The lettering overall appears somewhat irregular: the W in WILLIAM almost runs off the stone, the Ns in "DANDRIDGE" and "NOV." are upside down, "ASLEEP" is written out as "A SLEEP," the lettering is imperfectly horizontal at times, and the letter sizes and spacing within words is somewhat incongruous.

Comments: Pedestal with Virginiaulted top, standing atop a two-tiered base. The left side of the monument commemorates Kate, while the front (facing the plot entrance) commemorates her husband William.
Decoration: The top is a pointed arch with three-lobed interior border encompassing a crown carved in relief, set in the middle of a wreath (laurel?). Below the inscription is a band of leaves and berries (also laurel?) carved in relief. The same decoration is repeated on the back side of the tomb stone (without the inscription). The front side has similar decoration (with a large M in relief in place of the crown) and an inscription for her husband William Mitchell. The upper tier of the base on the front contains the name MITCHELL in relief lettering, bordered at top and bottom by a horizontal band with a recessed three-lobed / triconch Virginiault in the middle
Full transcription as it appears on the: KATE M. HARRIS | Wife of | WM A. MITCHELL | Born | May 29. 1870 | Died | July 29, 1907 | Rest in Peace

Description of photograph from Ohio Memory website (https://ohiopix.org/record-display/p267401coll32/15217): Description: This photograph from the Ohio Penitentiary in Columbus is of 24-year-old hospital employee Theodore "Ted" McClure. His formal attire suggests that the photograph was taken during his trial or sentencing. McClure was the 278th individual to be executed via the electric chair in Ohio. The caption at the bottom reads: “No. 278 Theodore Roosevelt McClure of Cuyahoga County, Legally Electrocuted May 10, 1950, for the Murder of Nicola Salnpo.” The victim's name is spelled Nicholas Salupo in period newspaper articles. In 1885 the Ohio Penitentiary in Columbus, Ohio, became the location for all executions, which previously took place in the various county seats. In 1896 the Ohio General Assembly mandated that electrocution replace hanging as the form of capital punishment. The Ohio Penitentiary regularly offered tours as well as souvenir photographs and postcards of the building and prisoners on death row. A total of 315 prisoners, both men and women, were executed in the electric chair known as “Old Sparky” between 1897 and 1963. View on Ohio Memory.
Image ID: AL08330

Notes and Clarifications: A marriage record exists for Caroline Hill (born c. 1864) to Robert Williams in King William County in 1889. The same Robert W. The family of Dr. and Mrs. R. F. Tancil express their thanks for the many letters of condolence, floral tributes and the kindnesses of the host of friends who extended their sympathy in the bereavement of our daughter, Mary L. Tancil, March 22, 1911. May God’s richest benediction rest upon each of you.
Other Documents to Consult for Research: Richmond Planet 19 Sept. 1903 (p. 1) mentions the "sweet solo of little Miss Mary Tancil" of Mt. Transcription of Printed Material: DR. R. F. TANCIL GONE  The funeral services of Dr. R. F. Tancil, one of the best known physicians and public spirited citizens in this State, took place from the Mt. Olivet Baptist Church, Rev. J. Andrew Bowler, the pastor officiating. The services were inspiring and sympathetic and a large crowd thronged the church edifice and packed the streets surrounding the place of the impressive ceremonies. Funeral Director Robert C. Scott, the well-known transporter of the dead, had charge of the remains.  Rev. Bowler was at his best and coupled with the solemn anthems of the choir and other selected singers, the exercises will long be remembered on Church Hill. It would fill a book to give a detailed account of Dr. Tancil’s work among these people, where he had chosen to reside. He left a daughter, Mrs. Pearl Tancil Langston, who is now a resident of Philadelphia; a son, Richard F. Tancil, Jr. Mrs. Tancil had preceded her husband to the grave. The services took place at twelve o’clock last Sundoy. [sic]

Occupation: Letter- carrier and vice president of branch 496, National Association of Letter-Carriers
Transcription of Printed Material: A Letter-Carrier Honored  Mr R. Bruce Evans, one of Richmond's most popular letter-carriers, and vice-president of branch 496, National Association of Letter-carriers, visited the recent unveiling in New York and was accorded a post of honor in the parade.  There were in line about 1400 letter-carriers in uniform, who were sub-divided and each division was under command of a station superintendent. Mr. Parsons, the National President desiring to honor Richmond had Mr Evans to assume the duties of station superintendent and coommand [sic] one of the division He was also presented with a handsome souvenir by Mr. Parsons. Infact, he was received and treated royally by the N w [sic] York carriers, and branch 496 appreciates the honor most highly.

Fraternal and Beneficial Organizations: A.F. Masons, Henrico Lodge No. 41; IOSL (Independent Order of St. Luke);
Transcription of Printed Material: A Good Man Gone. The funeral of Mr. R. Bruce Evans who departed this life suddenly on Monday morning lest while on his way his post of duty at the Richmond P. O., took place from the 4th Baptist Church on Wednesday evening the 25th inst. His pastor, the Rev. Jacob Turner of Mt. Tabor BaptisT Church officiating, adjusted by the pastor of the Fourth Baptist Church, the Rev. Evans Payne.  The deceased being a worthy young, licentiate of Mt Tabor Baptist Church in high esteem by the clergy of this city, and its vicinity as was evidenced by the presence of 21 pastors and aspirants, among whom were the following upon the rostrum: Revs. Jacob Turner, Evans Payne, J. H. Holmes, D. D., Wesley F. Graham, D. D. , J. H. Brice, P. S. Lewis, B D.. J. J, H. Binford, T. H. Briggs, P. C. Cobbs, J. Andrew Bowler, R. J. Bass, R. Beecher Taylor and D. Webster Davis, B. D. Short eulogies on the life and character of the deceased were delivered by several of the above named divines. Resolutions of Condolence were read by Revs. R. Beecher Taylor and J. Andrew Bowler, the latter on behalf of the Executive Board of the Virginia Baptist Sunday School Convention.  The choir of the Fourth Baptist Church, assisted by members of other choirs of the city and vicinity rendered music and the entire services were most impressive. Henrico Lodge, No. 41, Accepted and Free Masons, ol which he was a 32 degree member was in attendance; also Al Borsk Temple of the Mystic Shrine, on behalf of which most appropriate resolutions were read by Past Master Prof. Hugo Johnston. ' The Past Chiefs’ Council of the city of Richmond was well represented and furnished a handsome floral design, which was carried in a special carriage by Past W. Chiefs Maggie, L. Walker, Ella Onley, Emma Johnson, Mary Garrant.  Mt. Tabor Council, I. O of St. Luke, with which the deceased was connected for 20 years was out in large numbers, P. W. C., R. M. Monroe, presiding The PostMaster and the Superintendent of the Richmond Post Office, occupied seats upon the rostrum.  The floral designs which were many were furnished by station “A” of the Richmond Post Office, the National Carriers Association, the Main Office of the city, Union Prospect Council, I. O. of St. Luke of which he was a trustee, and by many dear friends whose names we could not get. The honorary pall-bearers were Messrs. E. A. Washington. W. M. T. Forrester, Eddie Cook and Rev. S. H. Dickerson. The active pall-bearers were representatives from the Virginiarious organizations with which the deceased was connected.
Notes and Clarifications: Religious Affiliation: Mt. Tabor Bapt. Church under R.V. Jacob Turner

Transcription of Printed Material: Mr. Evans’ Sudden Death.   This community was shocked on Monday morning, 23rd inst., to learn of the death of Mail-carrier R. Bruce Evans, who while on his way to work fell on Venable St., and died before he could reach home.  The immediate cause of his death was hemorrhage of the lungs. He was popular with all classes, being a prominent mason and St. Luke. He was a member of the Baptist Church at Woodville of which Rev, Jacob Turner is a pastor. Mr. Evans was also a licentiate minister. He waa a devoted husband and father.  His funeral took place at the Fourth Baptist Church. Rev. Turner preached an impressive sermon. Eulogies were delivered by visiting pastors.  Funeral Director W. Isaac Jchnaon officiated.
Notes and Clarifications: Member of the Baptist Church at Woodville under Rev. Jacob Turner

Title of Article/Chapter/Essay: H. F. Jonathan's Mother-in-Law Gone, Too.
Transcription of Printed Material: Death has once more hovered over the household of the late H. F. Jonathan. He died February 5, 1913 and twenty days later his wife's mother passes away under the same roof. ¶ Mrs. Mattie M. Robinson, widow of Sandy W. Robinson died at 749 N. 5th St., Tuesday, February 25, 1913 after a protracted illness. The funeral took place last Thursday at 1 o'clock from the Ebenezer Baptist Church. Funeral Directors W. Isaac Johnson and Sons had charge of the remains.

Transcription of Printed Material: OLIVER T. WILLIAMS' PUPILS IN MUSICAL RECITAL | Mr. Oliver T. Williams staged a highly successful recital Monday night. June 3rd at the Armstrong Auditorium at 8:15 o'clock. It surprised his friends and astounded his enemies (if he had any. The pupils showed rare ability and reflected the mastery skill of the instructor. The mandolin, cello, cornet, violin, guitar, tenor banjo and saxophone figured in the most enjoyable entertainment. A crowd of enthusiasts were present.

Transcription of Printed Material: The funeral of Ryland Lewis took place at the First Baptist Church last  Sunday at 1 o'clock. Rev. J. H. Fauntleroy read Psalm XXIII. Prayer was offered by Rev. Scott C. Burrell. Rev. W. T. Johnson delivered a most impressive sermon, "from the text, "God shall wipe away all tears from their eyes.” At the conclusion, Mrs. W. T. Johnson sang with transcendent sweetness of voice "In That City.” The letter from the distressed widow stated that death had come December 3 at 5:15 A. M. The deceased left a wife, son, sister, brother to mourn their loss.  He was a member of Invincible Lodge, No. 2674, G. U. O. of Odd Fellows, and also Venus Lodge, No. 46, Knights of Pythias. He had been a member of the First Baptist Church for more than twenty years.  Rev. Johnson and the congregation joined in singing "Sleep On, Beloved, Sleep and Take Thy Rest.” The floral designs were numerous and costly. The casket was cloth-covered, with heavy silver-mounted handles. Funeral director, A. D. Price, officiated. A touching letter of condolence was read from Mrs. Thomas M. Rutherford, in whose family he had labored so many years.

Transcription of Printed Material: Mr. Ryland L. Lewis Passes Away After an illness of two weeks, Mr. Ryland L. Lewis, husband of Mrs. Sarah Lewis and father of Mr. John H. Lewis passed away at his residence 815 Roane St., Thursday morning, December 3, 1914. at 5:15 o’clock. The funeral arrangements have not been completed as we go to press, the funeral to be from the First Baptist Church, Sunday Dec. 6th. 1914.

Width (in centimeters): 77 (lowest tier of base); 37.25 (inscribed portion of base)
Comments: Family marker at center of plot, accompanied by smaller markers for the individuals named on the obelisk. Evidence for repair or restoration, where a small piece of the obelisk above the base had broken off and was re-attached with adhesive of some kind.
Other Description: four-tiered base, with moldings and Virginiarying levels of polish (the inscribed area is most highly polished)
Decoration: One small horizontal line underlining the inscription on each side; lowest part of base unfinished or intentionally rusticated; obelisk itself is rough (unpolished) while the inscribed part is smoothly polished.
Full transcription as it appears on the: On side facing plot entrance (south): "REV. | CLAYBURN STORRS. | DIED FEB 20.1886 | AGED 77. YEARS."
Other Associated artifacts, plantings, o: conch shell beside; several tree stumps and one living tree inside plot, another growing through the plot border/fence; border of plot formed by granite posts with rusticated finish, horizontal metal bars between; plot entrance on south side, with threshold block inscribed "JACKSON & BRIGHT" in relief lettering.
Notes and Clarifications:
Probably set up in 1930 (when Maria Jackson died), since the plot entrance is labeled "JACKSON & BRIGHT." Were the earlier burials relocated?
Name spelled "Clayburn" on the obelisk and "Claiborne" on the small marker.

Transcription of Printed Material: Passed Away. Albright—Entered into eternal rest at the residence of her daughter Alice Albright, 311 1/2 E. Preston St., Thursday, January 13, 1916, 6:30 P. M., Mrs. Mary J. Albright, mother of the late Philip, Frank and Harrison Albright. She was a member of the First Baptist Church. Funeral, January 16, at one o'clock P. M. from the above residence, Rev. R. J. Bass officiating. The Reverend was at his best, preaching a pathetic sermon. The singing also was helpful and inspiring—"Savior Let Me Walk With Thee," and "Never Alone." The pallbeares [sic], both active and honorary were the immediate neighbors. Several handsome designs were sent by Captain Epps and his staff and friends of the deceased. She was laid to rest in Greenwood Cemetery in a handsome steel vault of late design. Funeral Director A. D. Price officiated.

Full transcription as it appears on the: G.W. SMITH | Departed this life. | Aug. 1, '09
Other Associated artifacts, plantings, o: This marker faces west at the end of a rectangular plot bordered by a low curb on three sides, composed of three rectangular slabs of concrete or soft stone, once secured by concrete. At the west side, there is no curb visible, but two rectangular posts seem to mark the entrance to the plot, on either side of the thin marker. A little further to the west is the marble socket base for a larger marble headstone (also for GW Smith) that now rests against the northern post. Inside the plot at the west side near the headstones and raised post are the fragments of at least two vessels (one ceramic with blue floral pattern, one white porcelain with relief design) and three conch shells.

Transcription of Printed Material: WILLIAMS - Died, suddenly,  June 24, at her residence, Mrs. Eliza Dennis Williams. She leaves to mourn her loss three brothers, two aunts, one uncle and host of other relatives. Remains are reposing at Randolph Funeral Home. Funeral Friday, 4 P.M., Fourth Baptist Church, Rev. J.A. Brown officiating, assisted by Rev. J.T. Crump

Notes and Clarifications: In 1910, Eliza (Lizzie A. Dennis) lived with her parents and five siblings on 3012 East N Street. In 1930, she was listed as the head of the household at 3008 P Street, living with her mother Mary, brother Samuel, and daughter Agatha (6 years old). Eliza was listed as a widow at the time of her death, and it is likely that her husband (?? Williams) had died before 1930. Agatha's death certificate lists her name as Agatha Louise Williams Dennis. While Eliza's death certificate gives her father's name as Lilton and his birthplace as New Kent County, Virginia, other sources (death certificates for Joseph and Samuel Dennis) list his name as Littleton and his birthplace as Maryland.
Other Documents to Consult for Research: death certificates for brothers Joseph and Samuel and daughter Agatha; US Federal Census 1910, 1930

Comments: Break on the left side and upper left corner of headstone. Break on right side and upper right corner of footstone appears to match, so it seems that this porcelain slab was broken in two pieces, and the larger was used for the headstone (did the break occur after the inscription had begun? That would explain why the footstone says only "ULYS."). The edges that are not broken are roughly squared and slightly beveled. The right side of the headstone is not exactly vertical. The back (uninscribed) surface of both the headstone and footstone are very smooth, while the front/inscribed surfaces have a fine-chiseled texture (except the bottom right corner of the headstone, which has a smooth concavity where a thin piece seems to have spalled off).
Other Description: Small thin slab headstone and smaller footstone that appear to be two joining fragments of the same stone
Full transcription as it appears on the: ULYSSESIMPSON | BORN APR 13 1927 | DIED 29 1950
Other Associated artifacts, plantings, o: Handcarved lettering. Both stones face east.

He rose to prominence in city politics, serving with distinction on the city council for nearly ten years. He represented Jackson Ward. He served on the board of the state's Central Lunatic Asylum, and he was a captain in the Attucks Guard, a local militia company. Entered into eternal rest Sunday, July 13. at the residence of her daughter-in-law, Mrs. Edna Murphy Morris. 2 110 Carrington Street, Mrs. Julia Covington, after an illness of several months. She had heen a faithful member of t li o Fifth Street Baptist Church for quite a number of years. She was a conscientious Christian, always ready to lend a helping hand. She bore her sickness with patience. She will be missed from the neighborhood being loved by all who knew her. Her funeral took place from the Mt. Olivet Baptist Church, Rer. Joseph Wheeler officiating. Her casket was a Spartan bronze metallic furnished by our popular young undertaker, Mr. Robert C. Scott. Interment in East End Cemetery.

Title of Article/Chapter/Essay: Mary White Dandridge Laid to Rest in East End Memorial Cemetery, Richmond, Virginia
Transcription of Printed Material: MARY WHITE DANDR1DGE LAID TO REST IN EAST END MEMORIAL CEMETERY, RICHMOND, Virginia Mary White Dandridge, daughter of the late Rev. G. and Mary A. White, who departed this life in New York City. Wednesday, June 9. 1926, was buried here Saturday at 2:30 P. M. The services in New York City were conducted by Rev. Dr. II. A. Booker and those in Richmond were conducted by Rev. Dr. S. C. Burrell, of the Y. M. C. A., assisted by Drs. W. T. Johnson, pastor of First Baptist Church; T. J. King, pastor of Fifth Street Baptist Church; A. D. Daly, pastor of Fifth Baptist Church; Dr. A. S. Thomas, Rev. G. Roane and others. Solo by Mrs. Ella P. Carter.  ihe services were impressive and consoling. The following members of the family accompanied the remains to Richmond: Rev. Dr. Thos. H. White, of Jersey City; Mr. Jos. White and Mrs. Martha E. Spencer and her daughter, Ruth D. Spencer, of New York City. The deceased leaves the following sisters and brothers, Mr. William White and Mrs. Elizabeth Jones, of Richmond. Virginia; Mr. Joseph White and Mrs. Martha E. Spencer, of New York City, and Dr. Thomas H. White, of Jersey City. The following gentlemen served as pallbearers: Honorary pallbearers —Messrs. W. H. Anderson, L. Storrs, Daniel Branch, John E. Scott, Rev. George Roane, Samuel Scott. Active pallbearers*—Messrs. James H. Brown, Joseph Poindexter, W. P. Logan, James Ullman. The following funeral directors, with great satisfaction to the family, directed the services: Messrs. W. C. Perry, of New York, and A. D. Price, Jr., of Richmond, Virginia

Transcription of Printed Material: (first note) J.E. Price - Und. 1120 North 25th Street Dear Sir: The certificate of death of Silas Thompson fails to state date of death Dec. 31-1932. (Second note) Dr. Walter Brown, 901 North 27th Street, Richmond, Virginia. Dear Sir: Our certificate #26509 is for the death of Silas Thompson, a colored man, aged 44 years, who died December 31, 1932. You give as the cause, "Nephritis," with the date of onset as November 15th, with "Bronchitis," date of onset October 15th, as contributory. Were you able to determine the cause of the acute nephritis? We do not ordinarily expect it to proceed from bronchitis. I would desire further to know whether you excluded tuberculosis of the lungs by State or city laboratory test, and if so, how many tests were made. Bronchitis is not a frequent cause of death for one as young as he. Reply on this letter in the enclosed penalty envelope which requires no postage. Very truly yours, W.A. Plecker, M.D. State Registrar Special Agent (Third note handwritten) Silas Thompson drank a great deal of bootleg whiskey prior to his illness which I think was cause of his nephritis. He did not have Tuberculosis. B.
Description of Printed Material: Correspondence between Doctor and State Registrar on the cause of death for Silas Thompson.
Notes and Clarifications:
Letter asks the writer of the certificate if they excluded tuberculosis of the lungs on the grounds that Bronchitis does not generally lead to death in a man that young, and is not usually lead to nephritis. 

The response at the bottom is that: 
1. Decedent drank a lot of bootleg whiskey which lead to nephritis 
2. Decedent did not have Tuberculosis

Title of Article/Chapter/Essay: 30 Yrs. For Murder / Mack Patterson Found Guilty Is Sent to Va. Penitentiary.
Transcription of Printed Material: Mark Patterson, Negro, in Hustings Court, was given thirty years in the penitentiary for the murder of Minnie Ford last March.  The evidence showed the assailant in a jealous frenzy went to the home of the girl and demanded an explanation of her alleged unfaithfulness.  As a result the girl was shot, and died later.  Harry C. Glenn, appointed boy the court, represented the accused.  Motion to set aside the verdict was overruled. Mack Patterson luckily escaped the electric chair for killing Minnie Todd, Sundayy night, March 3, 1928, at 2418 E. Main St.  That he was crazy drunk at the time was generally conceded.  The charge from the gun necessitated the amputation of her lim and soon thereafter she was a corpse.
